<TITLE> Eid being celebrated </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Muslims around the world are celebrating Eid-ul-Azha, or Festival of Sacrifice, a four-day holiday marking the end of the hajj pilgrimage. Islam marks its second largest festival with prayers and sacrifice. In Bangladesh, thousands upon thousands of people scrambled to get out of the capital of Dhaka and head to the provinces to join families for the holiday. A rush of commuters clogged the city's streets, ferries were full to bursting and trains crammed full. The festival of sacrifice represents Abraham's obedience to God and willingness to offer his own son. Families slaughter animals and donate the cuts to the needy. For the poor it's an annual treat. In the Gaza strip, which remains under Israeli blockade, the faithful prayed alongside Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh. In Indonesia, after prayers many headed to cemeteries to visit lost loved ones in another typical Eid tradition. And in Jerusalem's Old City, thousands came to the al-Aqsa mosque -- the second oldest in I
